and=20
writing files, and formatting output.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2><STRONG>Details:</STRONG> Write a =
program to=20
simulate a simple banking system.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>Your first task is to create a class =
called=20
<STRONG>Account</STRONG>. This class will store a person's account ID, =
passcode,=20
last name, first name, and balance. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>For your second task, you will create a =
class=20
called <STRONG>BankingSystem</STRONG>. This class must have at least the =

following functionality:</FONT></P>
<UL>
  <LI><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>Add a new account.</FONT><FONT=20
  face=3D"Times New Roman"><BR><BR></FONT>
  <LI><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>Delete an existing account.</FONT> =
<BR><BR>
  <LI><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>Inquire on an existing account (or =
all=20
  accounts).</FONT> <BR><BR>
  <LI><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>Save accounts to a file.</FONT> =
<BR><BR>
  <LI><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>Load accounts from a file.</FONT> =
</LI></UL>
<P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2><STRONG>BankingSystem</STRONG> must =
also use a=20
private data member that is declared as follows:</FONT></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2><STRONG>std::vector&lt;Account&gt;=20
  accounts_;</STRONG></FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>Your third task will be to develop a =
driver=20
program. The driver program will print some type of menu allowing the =
user to=20
choose the option they want. Instead of using a =
<STRONG>BankingSystem</STRONG>=20
object, you must use a pointer to a <STRONG>BankingSystem</STRONG> =
object with=20
the <STRONG>new</STRONG> operator. Your book describes this operator on =
pages=20
476-477. So, in your driver program, you would write the =
following:</FONT></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2><STRONG>BankingSystem* =
myBankingSystem =3D new=20
  BankingSystem();</STRONG></FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>At the end of your program, you have to =
free this=20
memory explicity by writing the following:</FONT></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2><STRONG>delete=20
  myBankingSystem;</STRONG></FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>Unlike previous projects, this one is =
very=20
open-ended. Besides my explicit requirements, you are free to make your =
own=20
design decisions. But, remember to use good programming practices. My =
sample=20
runs will give you a model you can follow for your driver =
program.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2><STRONG>Programming Tips:</STRONG> This =
project=20
rolls everything together into one. So, it is important to know the =
concepts=20
from the previous three projects. It may be helpful to create one =
function at a=20
time in <STRONG>BankingSystem</STRONG> and test it before proceeding. =
You can=20
also earn extra credit on this project by adding the following=20
features:</FONT></P>
<UL>
  <LI><FONT face=3DVerdana size=3D2>The ability to sort account =
inquiries by any of=20
